Predicting Chance of Diabetes Deep Learning Regression

Context

Diabetes is a growing global health concern. Early detection plays a key role in prevention and treatment. Using deep learning, we can build predictive models that help identify individuals at higher risk based on medical and biometric data.

Objective

To build and compare deep learning classification models that predict whether a person is likely to have diabetes (1) or not (0), using clinical features. The goal is to develop a model with strong generalization and minimal overfitting, suitable for future deployment.

Data Dictionary

  • Diabetes Dataset
    • Pregnancies: Number of pregnancies
    • Glucose: Glucose level in blood
    • BloodPressure: Blood pressure measurement
    • SkinThickness: Thickness of the skin
    • Insulin: Insulin level in blood
    • BMI: Body mass index
    • DiabetesPedigreeFunction: Diabetes percentage
    • Age: Age
    • Outcom: Final result 1 is Yes and 0 is No (Target Variable)

Build a feed forward neural network with 2 hidden layers and the output layer.

In[100]:
# We will be adding the layers sequentially
model_1 = Sequential()

# First hidden layer with 128 neurons and relu activation function, the input shape tuple denotes number of independent variables
model_1.add(Dense(128, activation='relu', input_shape=(8,)))

# We will be switching 20% of neurons off randomly at each iteration to avoid overfitting
model_1.add(Dropout(0.2))

# Second hidden layer with 64 neurons and relu activation function
model_1.add(Dense(64, activation='relu'))

# We will be switching 10% of neurons off randomly at each iteration to avoid overfitting
model_1.add(Dropout(0.1))

# Output layer with only one neuron and sigmoid as activation function will give the probability of students getting admitted into UCLA
model_1.add(Dense(1, activation='sigmoid'))

/usr/local/lib/python3.11/dist-packages/keras/src/layers/core/dense.py:87: UserWarning: Do not pass an `input_shape`/`input_dim` argument to a layer. When using Sequential models, prefer using an `Input(shape)` object as the first layer in the model instead.
  super().__init__(activity_regularizer=activity_regularizer, **kwargs)

Binary classification task, we will be minimizing the binary_crossentropy and we can choose one optimizer

  • SGD
  • RMSprop
  • Adam
  • Adadelta
  • Adagrad
  • Adamax
  • Nadam
  • Ftrl

Adamax optimizer with accuracy

  • Youre predicting 0 or 1 (Outcome), and Adam works very well with binary_crossentropy.
  • Adam handles gradients efficiently, even when features like Glucose, BMI, Age have different scales.
  • Adam is designed to work well even with fewer samples it adapts learning rates per parameter.
  • Compared to SGD or Adagrad, Adam usually converges faster without needing lots of hyperparameter tuning.

  • Observations
    • Training Accuracy steadily improves and peaks around 81%, indicating that the model learns well on the training data.
    • Validation Accuracy plateaus early at around 75% and begins to fluctuate, suggesting possible overfitting after ~60 epochs.
    • The gap between train and validation accuracy indicates that while the model generalizes reasonably well, further tuning (e.g., regularization or early stopping) may improve performance.

from tensorflow.keras.models import Sequential
from tensorflow.keras.layers import Dense, Dropout, BatchNormalization, Input

# Building Model 4
model_4 = Sequential()

# First hidden layer
model_4.add(Input(shape=(8,)))
model_4.add(Dense(128, activation='relu'))
model_4.add(BatchNormalization())
model_4.add(Dropout(0.3))

# Second hidden layer
model_4.add(Dense(64, activation='relu'))
model_4.add(BatchNormalization())
model_4.add(Dropout(0.2))

# Third hidden layer
model_4.add(Dense(32, activation='relu'))
model_4.add(Dropout(0.1))

# Output layer
model_4.add(Dense(1, activation='sigmoid'))

# Compile the model
model_4.compile(
    loss='binary_crossentropy',
    optimizer=tf.keras.optimizers.Adam(learning_rate=0.001),
    metrics=['accuracy']
)
